and I'm listening to you and I swear...</i>

451
00:31:20,266 --> 00:31:25,033
<i>...that I love you more than anything
in the world. And this is my moment.</i>

452
00:31:25,205 --> 00:31:29,005
<i>This strange conference-table moment.</i>

453
00:31:29,175 --> 00:31:31,075
<i>Turn off that camera!</i>

454
00:31:31,645 --> 00:31:35,137
<i>-This is my offering!
-No, I want this on the record!</i>

455
00:31:35,315 --> 00:31:36,543
<i>How do I turn it off?</i>

456
00:31:36,716 --> 00:31:40,243
<i>This is my offering. My clothes are
my offering. This is my shame.</i>

457
00:31:40,420 --> 00:31:43,185
<i>My credentials! I'm ashamed!</i>

458
00:31:43,357 --> 00:31:46,758
<i>And I love you, and I swear to God--</i>

459
00:31:54,468 --> 00:31:56,026
I guess that's it.

460
00:32:03,211 --> 00:32:04,508
When do we get Don?

461
00:32:05,113 --> 00:32:07,638
She said to try back in half an hour.

462
00:32:07,816 --> 00:32:10,717
And how about the flights?
What's the story at O'Hare?

463
00:32:11,953 --> 00:32:14,581
-Closed four minutes ago.
-Shit.

464
00:32:15,957 --> 00:32:18,357
There is a foot of snow
in Detroit already.

465
00:32:18,527 --> 00:32:20,791
Todd, could I get that coffee now?

466
00:32:22,998 --> 00:32:27,129
Who is this guy they sent from New York?
Clayton? I never heard of him.

467
00:32:28,938 --> 00:32:30,371
Michael Raymond Clayton.

468
00:32:30,540 --> 00:32:35,443
<i>Born September 9, 1959,
St. Joseph's Hospital, Bronx, New York.</i>

469
00:32:35,611 --> 00:32:39,308
<i>Father is NYPD patrolman
Raymond Xavier Clayton.</i>

470
00:32:39,482 --> 00:32:42,144
<i>Mother, Alice Mary Clayton.</i>

471
00:32:42,318 --> 00:32:45,481
<i>Graduates Washingtonville Central
High School, Orange County, New York...</i>

472
00:32:45,655 --> 00:32:47,283
<i>...in 1977.</i>

473
00:32:47,458 --> 00:32:51,827
<i>Graduates St. John's University, 1980.
Fordham Law, '82.</i>

474
00:32:52,496 --> 00:32:56,990
<i>'82 through '86, he's ADA with
the Queens district attorney's office.</i>

475
00:32:57,167 --> 00:33:00,102
<i>1986, he's with
the Joint Manhattan-Queens...</i>

476
00:33:00,270 --> 00:33:02,204
<i>...Organized Crime Task Force.</i>

477
00:33:02,372 --> 00:33:05,773
And then in 1990, he starts
at Kenner, Bach & Ledeen.

478
00:33:05,943 --> 00:33:07,376
So he's a partner?

479
00:33:08,279 --> 00:33:10,770
No. He's listed as special counsel.

480
00:33:10,949 --> 00:33:12,974
Says he specializes in wills and trusts.

481
00:33:13,885 --> 00:33:16,513
<i>He goes from criminal prosecution
to wills and trusts?</i>

482
00:33:16,688 --> 00:33:19,054
<i>He's been there 17 years,
he's not a partner?</i>

483
00:33:19,224 --> 00:33:22,887
<i>This is the guy they send?
Who is this guy?</i>

484
00:33:37,143 --> 00:33:39,407
-Hi.
-Close the door.

485
00:33:39,879 --> 00:33:43,872
All right. So nobody, none of you,
had any idea he was coming?

486
00:33:44,450 --> 00:33:46,315
To Milwaukee? For a deposition?

487
00:33:46,485 --> 00:33:50,046
We thought there was a settlement.
There's been some rumors.

488
00:33:50,222 --> 00:33:54,819
Okay. Look, it's very simple.
Arthur has a chemical imbalance.

489
00:33:54,995 --> 00:33:58,863
He's supposed to be taking his medication.
He's fallen behind on that.

490
00:33:59,032 --> 00:34:01,523
He's on the mend.
He'll be fine in three or four days.

491
00:34:01,701 --> 00:34:05,865
Now, I wanna make this crystal clear.
What happened here stays in this room.

492
00:34:06,039 --> 00:34:09,008
This is not a piece of information
you wanna be out in front of.

493
00:34:09,176 --> 00:34:12,475
Anybody has a problem with that,
I need to know right now.

494
00:34:13,614 --> 00:34:14,979
All right.

495
00:34:15,850 --> 00:34:17,681
We're stuck here overnight.

496
00:34:17,852 --> 00:34:20,150
I'm gonna take him
home tomorrow if I can.

497
00:34:20,321 --> 00:34:22,289
Who's in charge of
the deposition schedule?

498
00:34:22,456 --> 00:34:24,117
-I am.
-Where do we stand with that?

499
00:34:24,292 --> 00:34:26,487
I guess it's on hold.
We didn't know what to do.

500
00:34:26,661 --> 00:34:28,720
Nothing is on hold.
Keep doing what you were.

501
00:34:28,896 --> 00:34:31,160
Other side wants to talk,
they can call New York.

502
00:34:31,332 --> 00:34:34,392
-I need his briefcase.
-Arthur's? I don't-- I didn't see it.

503
00:34:34,569 --> 00:34:37,664
-He said it was in the room.
-It might be the stuff Jody grabbed.

504
00:34:38,040 --> 00:34:39,632
Find it.

505
00:34:45,614 --> 00:34:49,914
So all these people, they all start
having these dreams, okay?

506
00:34:50,085 --> 00:34:54,488
You know what a vision quest is?
You know, for, like, Navajos and stuff?

507
00:34:54,656 --> 00:34:57,922
<i>Yeah. I think so. Like a....</i>

508
00:34:58,294 --> 00:35:00,159
<i>Like a special dream.</i>

509
00:35:00,330 --> 00:35:04,892
Except this is like a whole bunch of people
having the same dream.

510
00:35:05,068 --> 00:35:08,469
They're all having this dream
that they should go to this one place.

511
00:35:08,638 --> 00:35:10,663
They don't know why or anything.

512
00:35:10,840 --> 00:35:13,968
They just have this feeling
that they have to go there.

513
00:35:14,143 --> 00:35:16,008
<i>That they've been summoned.</i>

514
00:35:16,179 --> 00:35:17,407
That's the chapter.

515
00:35:17,580 --> 00:35:20,550
Seriously, that's what it's called:
"Summons to Conquest."

516
00:35:20,718 --> 00:35:22,015
<i>That's the title.</i>

517
00:35:22,186 --> 00:35:27,852
Yeah, but do they know? Do they know
they're all having the same dream?

518
00:35:28,025 --> 00:35:29,993
<i>No. That's what's so cool.</i>

519
00:35:30,527 --> 00:35:32,461
They all think it's just them.

520
00:35:32,630 --> 00:35:36,691
That maybe they're, like, going crazy
or something, so they don't wanna admit it.

521
00:35:36,867 --> 00:35:38,994
Yeah, but they're not crazy, are they?

522
00:35:39,169 --> 00:35:42,662
<i>No. It's real. It's really happening.</i>

523
00:35:42,841 --> 00:35:46,470
Yeah, it is happening, isn't it?

524
00:35:47,679 --> 00:35:52,343
Something larger than themselves
and they're not ready, are they...

525
00:35:52,517 --> 00:35:54,314
...to hear it?

526
00:35:54,486 --> 00:35:56,386
Yeah. But later they will.

527
00:35:56,554 --> 00:35:59,387
So if you're gonna read it,
I don't wanna spoil it.

528
00:36:00,992 --> 00:36:02,824
What are you doing?
Who you talking to?

529
00:36:02,995 --> 00:36:04,963
<i>I called my dad. It's a friend of his.</i>

530
00:36:05,131 --> 00:36:08,396
<i>-Who?
-Mr. Edens. You don't know him.</i>

531
00:36:08,567 --> 00:36:11,229
<i>-Hello? Hello?
-Henry, it's after 11.</i>

532
00:36:11,404 --> 00:36:13,201
<i>I gotta get off now.</i>

533
00:36:13,372 --> 00:36:17,365
No. Wait, wait. The book.
I need the book. The title.

534
00:36:17,977 --> 00:36:20,207
<i>The book is Realm and Conquest.</i>

535
00:36:20,379 --> 00:36:22,142
Realm and Conquest.

536
00:36:22,315 --> 00:36:25,376
-It's Book One, with the red cover.
-Henry, give me the phone.

537
00:36:25,552 --> 00:36:28,112
I gotta go. Tell my dad I called. Okay?

538
00:36:28,989 --> 00:36:33,392
Yeah. Yeah. Thank-- Thank-- Thank--
Thank you, Henry, thank you.

539
00:36:37,597 --> 00:36:41,033
<i>Realm and Conquest. Thank you.</i>

540
00:37:04,258 --> 00:37:06,283
Karen? Hi, I'm Michael Clayton.

541
00:37:06,461 --> 00:37:07,929
-You're late.
-I know.

542
00:37:08,097 --> 00:37:10,622
I'm sorry, it was more complicated
than we thought.

543
00:37:10,799 --> 00:37:12,494
Where is he?
We've been here since 5:30.

544
00:37:12,668 --> 00:37:14,829
-He's asleep.
-Well, wake him up.

545
00:37:15,004 --> 00:37:17,268
That's not gonna happen.
We just got him sedated.

546
00:37:17,773 --> 00:37:20,799
Once he gets back
on his regular medication...

547
00:37:20,976 --> 00:37:22,910
...then it's just a matter of time.

548
00:37:23,078 --> 00:37:25,842
-Have you seen the video? The tape?
-I heard about it.

549
00:37:26,115 --> 00:37:28,583
What happened after is worse.

550
00:37:28,751 --> 00:37:32,654
This is in the parking lot, okay?
People running for their cars.

551
00:37:32,822 --> 00:37:34,949
He's there in his socks, nothing else.

552
00:37:35,125 --> 00:37:38,788
"I'm sorry. I'm so sorry.
I will not sit with this sickness any longer.

553
00:37:38,962 --> 00:37:41,760
I cannot aid this sickness any longer."

554
00:37:41,931 --> 00:37:43,523
What does this mean?

555
00:37:43,933 --> 00:37:45,491
I'm not sure.

556
00:37:45,668 --> 00:37:48,296
You've been with him the whole evening.
What's he saying?

557
00:37:48,471 --> 00:37:50,268
He wasn't really making much sense.

558
00:37:50,440 --> 00:37:51,999
This is totally unacceptable.

559
00:37:52,176 --> 00:37:55,111
This is a 3-billion-dollar
class-action lawsuit.

560
00:37:55,279 --> 00:37:57,213
In the morning, I have to call my board.

561
00:37:57,381 --> 00:38:01,943
I have to tell them that the architect
of our entire defense has been arrested...

562
00:38:02,119 --> 00:38:06,283
...for running naked in a snowstorm,
chasing the plaintiffs through a parking lot.

563
00:38:06,457 --> 00:38:08,254
I understand.

564
00:38:09,326 --> 00:38:11,351
What sickness is he talking about?

565
00:38:11,529 --> 00:38:14,158
-I don't know. It could be anything.
-Well, give me one.

566
00:38:14,332 --> 00:38:15,629
Frostbite.

567
00:38:16,134 --> 00:38:17,761
You think this is funny?

568
00:38:17,936 --> 00:38:20,200
Look, his wife was sick
and she died last year.

569
00:38:20,372 --> 00:38:24,832
His daughter doesn't talk to him.
He's all alone. All he does is your case.

570
00:38:25,010 --> 00:38:27,706
He skipped his pills.
He had a bad day. That's it.

571
00:38:27,879 --> 00:38:30,575
And you're somehow
the authority on this?

572
00:38:31,283 --> 00:38:33,808
His last episode was eight years ago.
I was there.

573
00:38:33,985 --> 00:38:36,819
I helped bring him home.
I watched him get better. That's it.

574
00:38:36,989 --> 00:38:40,755
Come on, Karen, you didn't hire this guy
because of his low-key regularity...

575
00:38:40,927 --> 00:38:43,919
...you hired him because he's a killer,
because he's brilliant...

576
00:38:44,097 --> 00:38:46,759
...because he's crazy enough
to grind away on this case...

577
00:38:46,933 --> 00:38:49,697
-...for six years without a break.
-We pay for his time.

578
00:38:49,869 --> 00:38:51,894
I thought you wanted an explanation.

579
00:38:52,071 --> 00:38:54,801
In the morning, I'm calling Marty Bach.

580
00:38:54,974 --> 00:38:58,001
But, then, you know that.
Thank you, Michael.

581
00:39:03,884 --> 00:39:05,977
He was mostly just quiet.

582
00:39:06,153 --> 00:39:09,020
I heard him moving around,
I gave him a pill 15 minutes ago.

583
00:39:09,189 --> 00:39:11,680
-He took it?
-A deal's a deal, right?

584
00:39:11,859 --> 00:39:13,588
A super job, Elston.

585
00:39:13,760 --> 00:39:17,423
You get to New York, you need tickets
to the game or anything, you let me know.

586
00:39:17,598 --> 00:39:19,032
I'll do that for sure.

587
00:39:39,420 --> 00:39:41,048
Did you see her?

588
00:39:41,390 --> 00:39:43,551
-Who?
-Anna.

589
00:39:44,093 --> 00:39:45,492
No.

590
00:39:46,695 --> 00:39:50,222
No, I didn't see her.
She probably went back to the farm.

591
00:39:51,100 --> 00:39:52,761
Well, we need her.

592
00:39:54,603 --> 00:39:59,404
Marty, even then, and the rest of them,
they won't understand.

593
00:40:00,476 --> 00:40:04,004
Well, if anybody can explain it to them,
it's you, Arthur.

594
00:40:05,715 --> 00:40:07,910
No, they're lost.

595
00:40:08,084 --> 00:40:11,144
-They have what they want.
-Let it go, man.

596
00:40:11,321 --> 00:40:13,152
This what you wanted?

597
00:40:14,758 --> 00:40:16,248
To be a janitor?

598
00:40:16,726 --> 00:40:19,786
Live like this? All this?

599
00:40:20,597 --> 00:40:22,258
Do what you do?

600
00:40:23,166 --> 00:40:25,067
It can't be.

601
00:40:25,937 --> 00:40:26,961
It's....

602
00:40:27,138 --> 00:40:30,767
It's a burden,
that's what I'm trying to tell you.

603
00:40:31,409 --> 00:40:33,536
That's-- That's how it feels.

604
00:40:34,478 --> 00:40:39,177
Well, I know that
we've been summoned.

605
00:40:40,952 --> 00:40:42,783
Get some sleep.

606
00:40:58,670 --> 00:40:59,694
<i>Hello?</i>

607
00:40:59,871 --> 00:41:03,671
Yes. Hi, I'm looking for Verne?

608
00:41:04,710 --> 00:41:06,041
<i>You have a number?</i>

609
00:41:06,211 --> 00:41:09,306
Don Jeffries gave me the number.
He said I could call at any time.

610
00:41:09,482 --> 00:41:11,347
<i>No. The account number.</i>

611
00:41:11,517 --> 00:41:15,715
The code? I do.
I have it right here. One moment.

612
00:41:17,657 --> 00:41:19,648
Excuse me one moment.

613
00:41:20,126 --> 00:41:23,721
It's right here. 12-BKR-6.

614
00:41:23,896 --> 00:41:25,955
12-BKR-6.

615
00:41:27,400 --> 00:41:29,391
Am I speaking with Verne?

616
00:41:30,504 --> 00:41:31,801
<i>It's Mr. Verne.</i>

617
00:41:31,972 --> 00:41:35,305
Mr. Verne. I'm sorry, it's so late.

618
00:41:35,476 --> 00:41:37,467
Don said that I could....

619
00:41:39,179 --> 00:41:41,409
I'm not exactly sure how this works.

620
00:41:41,582 --> 00:41:43,573
<i>Do you have e-mail
at your current location?</i>

621
00:41:43,751 --> 00:41:44,979
I do.

622
00:41:45,152 --> 00:41:47,313
<i>-Are you alone?
-I am.</i>

623
00:41:48,088 --> 00:41:52,321
<i>Okay, I'm gonna upload you
a little encryption package we like to use.</i>

624
00:41:52,494 --> 00:41:53,893
<i>It's pretty self-explanatory.</i>

625
00:41:54,062 --> 00:41:55,359
<i>-Okay.
-Okay.</i>

626
00:41:55,530 --> 00:41:58,499
<i>But you have to give me a minute
to get to my desk. Hold on.</i>

627
00:41:58,667 --> 00:42:00,362
Okay. Thank you.

628
00:42:24,627 --> 00:42:27,289
<i>What I was wondering is...</i>

629
00:42:27,463 --> 00:42:30,296
...I have an option on the lease
for six more years.

630
00:42:30,466 --> 00:42:33,128
I was wondering if there's any way
I could lay that off.

631
00:42:33,302 --> 00:42:36,295
Is the lease worth anything?

632
00:42:39,776 --> 00:42:42,267
Eighty-nine hundred a month. It's--

633
00:42:42,713 --> 00:42:45,443
The fixtures are gone, but there's--

634
00:42:47,150 --> 00:42:50,347
But there's the bar, there's a kitchen,
it's a great space.

635
00:42:51,922 --> 00:42:53,480
But there's a--

636
00:42:57,795 --> 00:43:00,889
Yeah, I understand. No, I understand.

637
00:43:02,667 --> 00:43:04,760
Okay, yeah, I will.

638
00:43:05,403 --> 00:43:06,927
All right. Thanks.

639
00:43:17,281 --> 00:43:18,873
Come on, Arthur.

640
00:43:21,487 --> 00:43:22,784
Arthur!

641
00:43:24,256 --> 00:43:25,348
Arthur, open the door.

642
00:43:28,927 --> 00:43:30,792
Arthur, open the door!

643
00:43:33,632 --> 00:43:36,032
Arthur, open the goddamn door!

644
00:43:37,336 --> 00:43:38,598
Arthur, op--!

645
00:43:39,405 --> 00:43:41,499
Open the fucking door!

646
00:43:47,881 --> 00:43:49,348
Arthur!

647
00:43:50,150 --> 00:43:52,778
Goddamn it, Arthur! Open the fucking--!

648
00:44:03,230 --> 00:44:04,424
Arthur?!

649
00:44:15,743 --> 00:44:17,574
-Mr. Verne, hey.
-Hey, Danny.

650
00:44:17,745 --> 00:44:20,009
You guys are early.
I was pulling the other bags.

651
00:44:20,181 --> 00:44:23,048
You can put them back.
There's been a change of plans, sorry.

652
00:44:23,217 --> 00:44:25,118
-We ready?
-Yep.

653
00:44:29,257 --> 00:44:31,316
For chrissake.

654
00:44:31,493 --> 00:44:33,358
Don Jeffries signed this?

655
00:44:33,829 --> 00:44:36,389
That's really his signature?

656
00:44:36,565 --> 00:44:38,533
Where's the original?

657
00:44:38,700 --> 00:44:43,763
We had a warehouse fire five years ago.
We lost a number of documents.

658
00:44:49,879 --> 00:44:52,746
What the hell is this doing
in Arthur's bag?

659
00:44:53,382 --> 00:44:54,906
Well, I don't know, Marty.

660
00:44:55,084 --> 00:44:59,043
That's something I was hoping
you might be able to tell me.

661
00:45:03,793 --> 00:45:05,385
What are we looking for?

662
00:45:05,561 --> 00:45:09,760
If it says U/North, pull it aside.
Anything that says U/North.

663
00:45:11,235 --> 00:45:12,725
What a mess this is.

664
00:45:17,374 --> 00:45:18,602
I want all this...

665
00:45:19,543 --> 00:45:23,639
...everything here, I want it all packed up
and sent up to the house.

666
00:45:24,748 --> 00:45:26,147
Any luck, Michael?

667
00:45:26,884 --> 00:45:30,981
He booked a limo from Newark Airport at 3,
got out at West Fourth Street...

668
00:45:31,155 --> 00:45:33,123
...tipped the driver 100 bucks
and walked away.

669
00:45:33,291 --> 00:45:34,485
Did you try his apartment?

670
00:45:34,659 --> 00:45:35,819
-He moved.
-I know.

671
00:45:35,994 --> 00:45:38,360
It's a loft. No doorman.
I rang, nobody answered.

672
00:45:38,530 --> 00:45:41,192
-I called, I got the machine.
-So he could be anywhere.

673
00:45:41,366 --> 00:45:44,358
Arthur downtown is not a good idea.
Some goddamn loft.

674
00:45:44,536 --> 00:45:47,266
-Where's his daughter?
-I don't know. Spain, lndia.

675
00:45:47,438 --> 00:45:50,566
Mars. She's crazier than he'll ever be.

676
00:45:50,742 --> 00:45:52,574
Barry's taking over on U/North.

677
00:45:52,745 --> 00:45:54,542
We got a lot of groveling to do.

678
00:45:54,713 --> 00:45:56,806
You didn't exactly charm Karen Crowder.

679
00:45:56,982 --> 00:45:58,210
I was punting.

680
00:45:58,384 --> 00:46:01,046
You gotta saddle up here
and get things under control.

681
00:46:01,220 --> 00:46:02,209
Saddle up?

682
00:46:02,388 --> 00:46:05,448
He needs to be under a doctor's care.
He needs to be admitted.

683
00:46:05,624 --> 00:46:07,956
-Where?
-Does that really matter?

684
00:46:08,127 --> 00:46:11,028
Michael, U/North needs to know
he's under control.

